    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Trenches of War</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Michael West disputes Robert D Kaplan's depiction of style of warfare between Eritrea and Ethiopia (May 23 Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Robert D. Kaplan (Op-Ed, May 23) says Eritrea and Ethiopia, though physically in Africa, are not really a part of that continent but can instead be seen as ''a fragment of the Middle East dislodged from Eurasia.'' This, he says, is evidenced by their style of warfare, which bears greater resemblance to the Iran-Iraq war of the 1980's than to ''any African conflicts of the past decade.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Robert D. Kaplan (Op-Ed, May 23) says Eritrea and Ethiopia, though physically in Africa, are not really a part of that continent but can instead be seen as ''a fragment of the Middle East dislodged from Eurasia.'' This, he says, is evidenced by their style of warfare, which bears greater resemblance to the Iran-Iraq war of the 1980's than to ''any African conflicts of the past decade.''</p>
        <p>But such logic points to European rather than Middle Eastern antecedents for the senseless war between Eritrea and Ethiopia. The fierce trench warfare that has consumed so many tens of thousands of soldiers on both sides was infamously pioneered by Western Europeans in World War I.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL WEST  Somerville, Mass., May 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
